  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Key instruments include:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention requires signatory countries to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking. It was one of the first international efforts to address money laundering.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** FATF is an inter-governmental body established in 1989. While not a treaty, its **40 Recommendations** are the international standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries have incorporated these recommendations into their domestic laws. FATF also monitors countries' implementation of these standards and publishes lists of jurisdictions with deficiencies in their AML/CFT regimes.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the criminalization of money laundering beyond drug-related offenses to cover a wider range of serious crimes.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention) and its revised version (2005 Warsaw Convention):** These conventions focus on international cooperation in investigating, prosecuting, and confiscating the proceeds of crime, including money laundering.\n\nThese instruments establish frameworks for:\n\n*   **Criminalizing money laundering:** Defining money laundering as a crime and setting penalties.\n*   **Customer due diligence:** Requiring financial institutions to identify and verify the identities of their customers.\n*   **Record-keeping:** Mandating that financial institutions maintain records of transactions for a certain period.\n*   **Reporting suspicious transactions:** Requiring financial institutions to report transactions that may be related to money laundering or terrorist financing.\n*   **International cooperation:** Facilitating the sharing of information and evidence between countries in investigations and prosecutions of money laundering.\n*   **Confiscation of assets:** Enabling the seizure and forfeiture of assets derived from criminal activity.\n\nIt's important to note that the enforcement of these international laws relies on individual countries incorporating them into their domestic legislation and actively cooperating with each other. The level of enforcement varies considerably across different jurisdictions.",
